nlocal public 1elief pfforts\nIn accordance with v e coge\nthe Congrecs passed the Federal|\nEmergency Relief Act. approved by\nme May 12, 1030\nNEY RELIEF POLICY\nThe statute was expressive of the!\nnew Government attitude\nFirst, it recognized that relief was\na social problem ot he administered\nby a social ager rather than by\nthe Reconstruction Finance Corpor\nation, which was nrely 2 financial\nagency.\nSecond. provide for outright\ngrants to States instead of the prior\nsystem of making loans \u2018o States re.\npayable out of future highwav grants\nThird, it definitely recognized il ,1\u2018\nrelief was not the conplete respons\nibility of the States and their local\npolitical subdiv. ions, and that the\nFederal Government hid its share nf}\nresponsibility where Tocal and State\nresources proved nadequate. I\nWhen, as Governor of New York\n1 set up Temprorary Emergency\nRelief Administeation in 1971, to ad.\nminister State approprintions of\nmoney for direct aid 1o the Tacalities\n1 appointed Harry L. Hopkins as e\nhead. When thic new national\nagency was set up in 1933 T appoin\ned him Administratig\nThe task he wirs stupendous\nLittle was known at Washington\nabout the efficiency of the local reo\nlief organizations. There were no\nsuch organizations in come State\nand inmany counties\nAction hatl to be unmedoate.\nwas immediate The dav after he\ntook office, an May 22 1930 he tele\ngraphed his first communication to!\na\nAre You\nAdequately\nProtected!\nWk s ^_. HMEH\nPHONE 751\nFOR A REPRESENTATIVE\nof INSURANCE\nROARK INSURANCE\n-AGENCY-\nHAMILTON HOTEL BLDG.\nFeci Secure\nknowing that your home. too. i* pro*\n,trrtcd against the |\u00bbo**ihlr loss caused\nby high winds. heck up SOW' Be\n?urr that you arc adequately covered\nwith\nTORNADO\nINSURANCE\nlion.\nAO Forms\nWith the depression at its deepest point, as President Roosevelt was about to take office in 1933, bread\nlines formed not only in principal cities, hut in most small communities as well. Here is a hreadline\nin Times Square, New York City, where men were glven food from a truck.\n1he Governors of ine reLpective\nStatec and before niginfall he had\nmiade gants of mones to Colorado\nNinoie, lowa, Michigan, Mississippi,\nObio andd Texas\nFron: the very heginnng two am\nportanat points of policy were evid\nent. (1 The operations o fthe pro\ngram, avde from certain basic stand\nards and storpalations were 1o be\ndecentialized and local in character,\nand 020 work, rather than idleness\nan a daole, was preferred\nAgain and again 1 found ie neces\niy torepeat the primciple that\nwhen the locality has done all it can,\nthe obligaton is on the State to 1\nto complete the unfinished job, and\nthat only after the State and the\nlocahitics have done their utmoms!\nshould Federal funds be provided.\nThe FERA in Washington was con\ncerned primanily with the granting\nof funds to the Governors of States\nAfter the grant was made, the funds\nbeca e the pooperty of the State\nandd were thus bevond divect adinin\nistiative control of the FERA. Virt\nvally ol the SE114000,000 expended\nthrough this cooperative Federal-\nState local relief system from June,\n1933, through August, 19360 was dis\nhursed by the local offices\nThe program provided for either\nwark relief or divect relief 1o a des\ntitute family. according to s needs,\nas determined by investigation. Fam\nilies sometine had no member able\nto work, or communities did not have\npublic projects on which to em\nploy them. In these cases the needy\nwere cupplied directly with cash or\nwith groceries fuel, clothing and\nother necessities\nApproximately 2000000 persons\nwere engaged o work velief in\nMarch, 1933 and 1500000 in Novem\nher\nIn thewe early monthe of the pro\ngram, reliefl worke projects were car\nried out entirely. by local officials\nwithout anyv Federal visa. Much\nwas excellent and of pronounced\npermanent value, but a considerahle\nquantity was too hastily planned or\nof the \u201cleal raking\u201d 1ype\nCWA CREATED\nI November, 190330 40 new emer\ngency hrought about the creation of\nanother relief ageney by Executive\nOvder, the Civil Works Admimistra\ntion (WA\nI decided to anitiate the CWA at\nthic time o a number of reason\nRelief needs continued with incereas\nmg sevioness as the winter months\ncame on. The sharp business revival\nof the summer months had ceased;\nARTICLE 4\nand, indeed, a reaction had set in\nThe velief rolls which had declined\nsharply from March, 1933, had be\ngun to o rise ageor on October, 1933\nThe Public Wearks Admimistration\n(P.W A had ot been able by that\ntime to commence a very extensive\nprogram of large public works\n[T eame to the conclusion thht by\nshifting ta th's new (WA program\nL0000 peaple enployed in o local\nwork rehief activities, and other em\nplovable who were then on direct\nrelief. a great quantity of purchas\ng power could be mjected into the\neconomic system inoa short time;\nthat the direct relief rolls would be\ngreatly reduced; and that adequate\nwages for -useful projects would be\nsubstituted for inadequate pay on\nwaork of little value.\nIts organization and operation wera\nCessentially different from that of the\nFERA which vas mostly a State\nand local program. The CW.A. was\ncompletely aperated and 90 per cent\nfinanced by the Federal Government\nBy the end of November, more\nCthan 15000000 persons were at work\ncon CW.AL projects, and in January,\n1934, the C.W. A reached its peak\nof 4263644 workers earning more\nCthan $64.000.000 per week\nThe CW A was not designed a:\nTn continuing program. By the end\nof March, 1934, it was largely ter\n~minated, dehpite widespread pres\nsure to make 1t permanent\ni CW A was relatively costlv, when\ncompared with the FFERA and as\n\\snnn as s prime purpose was he\nlieved to have heen served, it was\nabandoned in favor of 4 work relief\nCprogram hiving only destitute un\nemployed on a budgetary deficienc\nbasis. The step was taken as a mat\nter of econann\nIn evaluating the benefits of CW.A\nthere must he taken into considera\ntion the 1933 necesaity for such a\nprogram, the speed with which it\nwas inaugurated, and its qinck !r\u2018lm\u2014'\nmation within five months, It pro\nvided definite proof that an exten\nsixe work: program could be quicsl\nand profitably undertaken with\nbhenefit to the communities and o the\nunemploved\nUpon the disolution of the CW.A\nthe FERA agaon fostered Lage\nseale work relief, called the Emer\ngeney Work Rehef Procoon R\nFanuary, 1935, 1t employment peak\no 2000000 wae reached However\nduring this perod, more cises were\nrehef\n\nWORKS PROGRESS\nADMINISTRATION\nThe next great step i the pro-\nTHE LAREDO TIMES, SUNDAY, MARCH 27, 1938\n\"gram of relief wasz taken bv the or\nganization, in 1995, of the Works\nProgress Adiinistration\nThere had bheen a growing con\nviction on the part of the Congress\nand myself that the time had come\nwhen the Federal Government could\nwell afford to withdraw from the\n\u2018Iic-ld of direct relief, leaving that\nresponsibility to the various States\n;nml localities, and to establish a\nllarlzr-r works program,\nMy Executive Order of May 6. 1935,\nestaMlished the Works Progress Ad\nministration (WP.A) as the key\nagency in the Federal Works Pro-\u2018\nBram.\nThe Works Program is the term\nused to designate the entire program\ninf emergency work provided by the\nEmergency Relief Appropriation Acts\nof 1935, 1936, and 1937, Forty Fed\n|(>|:|I agencies participated in it in-|\ncluding Recettlement Administration\n(R. A Rural Flectrification Ad-\nCministration (RE.AD, National Ynuthi\nAdministration (N.Y.A), and Works.\nProgress Administration (WP.A).\nWorks Progress Administration wah\ncharged with the responsihility for an\nhonest, efficient, speedy and cnnrd-\u2019\nJnated execution of the work relieff\nprogram a. a whole. Tt was the larg-\nest emplover, by February, 1926, it\nhad reached a peak of over three\nmillion persons\nThe Works Program had the ad-|\nvantage of the experience of the'\nprior agencies in large-scale emer\ngeney work relief. It left the en-|\ntire responsibility for direct relief\nfor unmeplovables to the States and\nlocalit es,\nWith respect to work projects, the\nState and local governments were\ngiven the responsibility, with few\nexceptions. of originating and plan-!\nning the work to fit I -al needs and\nalsa of determining the eligibility of\nworkers on the basis of actual need.\nAt the same time, through Federal!\napproval of e projects and\nthrough the carryving out of a Fed\neral wages and hours policy and by\nmeans of Federal accounting and\npurchasing, there were obtained a\ngeneral centralized planning and\nresponsibility\nIn view of the fact that the prin\ncipal purpose of v P.A. was to pro\nvida work Federal approval was\ngiven onlv to projects which could\nbe carried out by t'e type of un\nemploved warkers available in the\nrespective commun tie The aim\nwas to obhtam projects o oeach om\nmunity which could he performed\nby the T of workers in that com-\nmunity whe were emplovable.\nWP inoits waoe policy souzht ta\nprovide an cared monthly \\m-nmt\u2018!\ncalled a security wage,\u201d slightly\nhigher than the inco. e from direct\nrelief but lower than the monthly\nwages in private employvment. In\narder to meet the criticism that the\nlow relief wages would drag down\nprevatiing hourly rates of other\nIabor, the poiley was adopted in 1936\nof paving prevatlirg hourly wages\nbut reducyin the hours of work so\nthat total wrnings +~mained at sec\nurity wage levels. i\nThe future need of a Federal Wark\nRelief Agency will depend, of eourse.\nupon the trend of husiness and the!\nsupply of private jobs. but the out\nlines of a sound national policy for\nwork relief have hecome fixed\nthrough the long experience which\nculminated in W.P.A, i\nMIND Your\nMANNERS\nTEST vour knowledge of cor\nreet social usage by answering\nthe following questions, then\nchecking against the authoria\ntive answers below:\n1. At a public dinaer where the\nspeaker\u2019s table is long and narrow\nis it customary for the guests to be\nseated on one side of the table enlv?\n2. Where doe the chairman or\ntoastmiaster st at such a table?\n3. Mav one use qust first names on\nplace cards where the guests are few\nn number and all are intimate\nfriends\u2019\n4 Is it preferable to use plain\nwhite place cards or fancy colored\nones?\n5 1f there 1= no woman guest of\nhenor at a dinner party, who is seat\ned at the hoat's yrght?\nWhat would you do if\u2014\nYour are writing names on place\ncards for a good-sized dinner party?\nWrite an individual's name as\u2014\nta) Mrs. Charles Davis,\n(hy Mrso \u20ac0 B Davis,\n(el Mrs, Davis,\nANSWERS\n1. Yes\n2 In the center,\nA Ves\nPlamm ones. Unuzusl one: are\nnyol for feature parties\n5 Generally the eldest woman.\nBest \u201cWhat Would You Do solu\ntion\u2014(c) unless theve is likely to he\nanother with the name of Davis\u2014\nthen use (a).\n(Copyright, 1038, NEA Service, lnc.)\nMonterrey Social News\nMisses Mercedes and Carmen Rodriguez are spending a short time\nvisiting in San Antonio, Texas.\nMrs. Ullysses Berthier and daughters, Mary Gertrude and Kax,\nhave returned from San Antonin, Texas. Mary Gertrude, who is attend\ning the Ruth Coit School in San Antonio, will spend the spring holidays\nin. Monterrey,\nDick Harbordt spent the weekend in Monterrey visiting his father and\nmother, Mr. and Mrs, George Harbordt,.\nMr. Theodore Wuerpel has moved into his spacious new rome in Co\nlonia Mitra,\nMrs. Clift Young cgtertained on Saturday with a beautifully appointed\nluncheon at her home in Colonia Mirador, Spring flowers formed the note\nof decoration and places were marked for Mrs. Hugh White, Mrs. Charles\nHoke, Mrs. William Blocker, Mrs. Pear] Maddox of Austin, Texas, Mrs.\nJ. M. Palma of Mexico City, Mrs. Eduardo Villarreal, Mrs. Rufus Mc\u2014!\nNees, Mrs. Rae DeButts of Lincoln, Neb., Mrs, Earle Van Buskirk and\nthe hostess.\nMr. and Mrs. Earnest Smith, Mr. and Mrs. George Nelis and Mr. and\nMrs. A. Lindsay of Denver, Colorado arrived in Monterrey on Saturday\non their way to Tampico for their annual fishing trip. After a few days\nin Monterrey Messrs. Smith, Nelis and Lindsay will leave for Tampico and!\ntheir wives will continue their visit here, Mr, and Mrs. Nelis are the\ni house guests of Mr. and Mrs. Frank Hobson, while other members of the\nparty are at the Hotel Ancira. Many informal social affairs have been\nplanned for the visitors during their stay in Monterrey where they have a\nhost of friends who welcome them back each year, On Sunday evening\nMr. and Mrs, Frank Hobson complimented the out of town guests with a\ncocktail party, later attending the regular Sunday night dinner dance at\nthe Casino Monterrey. Additional guests invited were: Mr. and Mrs,{\nUllvsses Berthier, Mr. and Mrs. James Mackay, Mr. and Mrs, Robert Head,\nMr. and Mrs. Ben Lange, Mrs. J. M. Palma of Mexico City and Mr, and\nMrs. George Doughman,\nMr. Jack Halbert of Terreon, Coahuila, spent Thursday and Friday in\nthe city.\nA most delightful eocktal and dinner party was given by Mr. and\nMrs. Robert Head at their home on Calle Hidalgo on Saturday evening\ncomplimenting a number of their friends. Spring flowers in various colors\nformed the decorative note throughout the livingrooms and diningroom and\nfollowing dinner, games of cards were arranged; guests for the evening\nincluded: Dr. and Mrs. Hugh White, Mr. and Mrs. Eduardo Villarreal, Mr.\nand Mrs, William Blocker, Mrs. Pearl Maddox of Austin, Texas, Mrs. J.\nM. Palma of Mexico City, Mr. and Mrs. George Doughman, Mr. and Mrs.\nOtto Withoff; Mr. and Mrs. George Nelis, Mr, and Mrs, Earnest Smi!hi\nand Mr. and Mrs. A. Lindsay of Denver, Colorado, Mr, and Mrs. Clift\nYoung, Dr. arsl Mrs. Baba Thomas, Mr. and Mrs. Wier Marshall, Mrs.l\nPhilip Messenger and Mr. and Mrs, Frank Hobson.\nMr. and Mrs. George Harbordt left on Sunday evening for Baltimore,\nMaryland, where Mr. Harbordt will undergo treatment at the Johns\nHopkins Medical Clinic. Mr. and Mrs. Harbordt expect to be away abouli\ntwo months, They were accompanied by Dr. Miguel Vera, who will make\n!the trip with them.\n\nMr. Paul Harrington of Denver, Coloradn arrived in Monterrey on Sun\ndav and will spend some time here visiting his sister, Mrs. Frances\nWilliams.\nMonday being Ladies Day at the Monterrey Country Club, a play\nagainst hidden par was the contest for the afternoon. with Mrs. Charles\nHoke winner Later the players were joined by their husbands and a bas-l\nket supper, followed by games of cards, was enjoyed. About a hundred\nmembers were present. In the Ladies First Quarterly Handicap Golf\nTournament. Mrs. Ben Lange and Mrs. Clift Young have reached the\nfinals. with thirty-six holes of golf to be played before the first of April.\nIn the Men's First Quarterly Handicap Golf Tournament, Messrs, Vir\ngilio Garza, Jr.. and Mauro Uribe Jr., will play off the finals.\nA great deal of interest is being shown in the Annual Golf Tourna\nment to be held in Tampico on the 14th., 15th. and 16th. of April; this is\nan invitational tournament and many Monterrey golfers are preparing to\nattend\nThe Thursday Bridge and Golf Club met this week with Mrs, Otto\nWithoff as hostess for luncheon, only members were present.\nMrs. Chift Young entertained with luncheon and bridge on Wednesday\nat her home in Colonia Mirador complimenting Mrs. George Nelis, Mrs.\nEarnest Smith and Mrs. A. Lindsay of Denver, Colorado. Cut flowers of\nvaried colors were used as table decorations and to adorn the living rooms;\nat the conclusion of the games, most attractive handpainted Spanish tiles\nwere awarded as table prizes, Mrs. Lange and Miss Fairchild being the.\nwinners. Besides the honorees. Mrs. Younz's guests were: Mrs. James\nMaclkay. Mrs. Wier Marshall, Miss Margarita Fairchild, Mrs, Ben Lange\nand Mrs. Frank dobson.\nMiss Maria Antonia Salinas celebrated her birthday anniversary on\nthe 19th with a delightful merienda, given at the home of her parents,\nMr. and Mrs, Emidgio Salinas; places being laid at the beautifully dec\narated table for: Mr. and Mrs. Jose Madrigal, Mr. and Mrs Jose Barrera\nLopez. My and Mrs. Emidgio Salinas, Mrs, Natalia Mattei de Garcia,\nMi ses Lidia, Estela and Otalia Salinas, Maria and Graciela Blanco, Micaela\nMacias Me;ssrs. Maximiliano Salinas, Delfino Garcia, Ubelestes and Fran\ncisco Garcia and Dr. Alfredo de la Garza.\nMrs. Martinez de Urdiales, accompanied by Misses Hermelinda and\nIlva Urdiales, Maria Luisa Guzman and Alicia Cantu, left on Wednesday\nFRIGIDAIRE\nfem emr bulk! Saws up to 25% MORK\nSEE OUR 4-WAY SAVING DEMONSTRATION\nPER WEEK!\nCUTS CURRCNT COST D\u00a3\u00a3P\u00a3R TM/V\u00a3l/\u00a3R!\nMeter-Mfeer of 1937. ComHerrfy\nsealed. Automatically oiled and cooled.\nTERMS AS\nLOW AS\nhacked by GENERAL MOTORS.\nCome In. See-hear-the PROOF of fas\nWhen you buy a refrigerator, be sure that it saves in\nALL 4 WAYS on current, food, ice, upkeep For some\nrefrigerators may save you money in one, two or even\nthree ways only to waste it in some \u201chidden eyfravm\ngance\u201d! Play safe! Come in and see the 1938 Frigidaire\nin every model, a \u201cDoable-Easy\" Qnirkniw\nTeeyt No other She it! See PROOF\u2019\nOwfr Frigidoire\nha\u00ab them I\nwith NEW Silent Meter-Miser that saves\nyou more in every way there is to save!\nSaves ACL 4 WA YS You see the Proof\nbefore your eyes, before yon buy! See,\ntoo, Frigidaire\u2019s NEWLY-Styled 9 Way\nAdjustable Interior! NEW \u201cDouble-\nEasy\u201d Qttickube Trays throughout!\nNEW Moisture-Seal Hydnitors? NEW\nClose-Bar Sliding Shelves... and dozens\nmore exclusive advantages. To be sure\nof full 1938 value in a refrigerator\nSEE FRIGIDAIRE FIRST!\nCUM IN! LISTEN TO THE NEW\nSILENT METER-MISER\nto Bale torrent\u2014Yau tout bartOr boor\nNEW \u201cDOUBLE-\u00a3ASY\u201d QUICKOBE TRAYS\nCA L RELEASE CUBES INSTANTLY\nvXVf ryt -SAVE 20% MORE ICE! Onfrone\nj\u00ae\u2019. I leverto Eft and cubes are released\n^^^gEEEEL\\ydf \u20142 of tMyftrfl AJI-tnetwi for faster\n111 I faeeaing! No melting under frocet!\nTRAYS COME FREE AT FIN\n4\u2014GER-TOUCH with exHnsrue\n1 i in't iTT\nor you may not Save of a//!\nPHONE 551 FOR FREE DEMONSTRATION!\nI HALSELL ELECTRIC CO.\nSALINAS AT LINCOLN STS.\niLw SILENT METER-MISER\nSaves More not only on Current, but on Food-Ice-Upkeep!\nfor her homie in Guadalajara, where the Misses Urdiales, Gusman and Cante\nwill be her guests for some time.\nMrs. Mercedes L. de Leon and daughters, Lolita and Maria Mercedes,\nwho have spent several weeks visiting in Monterrey, have, left for their\nhome in Guadalajara.\nMr. Julio Madero, who has spent the last few weeks in Monterrey\ncombining both business and pleasure, left for his home in Mexico City.\nMr. Madero is director of the National Lottery.\nA lovely hospitality of the spring season was the golf and bridge\nluncheon given at the Monterrey Country Club on Thursday by Mrs, Frank\nZierer and Mrs. Frank Hobson complimenting a number of their friends\nand several out of town visitors. The spacious lounge room of the cluB\nhouse was gay with bowls and baskets of vari-colored flowers, which also\ncentered the 'small tables which were laid with blue and white pesln!\ncloths and Mexican blue glass, Following the serving of \u2018luncheon, tables\nwere arranged for contract bridge and foursomes of golf were made up;\nattractive\u2019 prizes being awarded at the conclusion of the games. Guest\nlist included: Mrs. Tomas Rodriguez, Mrs. Alexander Tosi, Mrs, John\nWoods, Mrs. Earle van Buskirk, Mrs. Joe Bowers, Mrs. Coleman Gregory,\nMrs. Clift Young, Mrs. Wier Marshall, Mrs. James Mackay, Mrs. aBba\nThomas, Mrs. Edwin Richards, Mrs. Walter Miller, Mrs, James McMains,\nMrs. Paul Demille, Mrs. Luis Trevifio, Mrs. Arthur Abernathy, Mrs. J.\nM. Palma of Mexico City, Mrs, George Nelis, Mrs. A, Lindsay and Mrs.\nEarnest Smith of Denver, Colorado; Mrs. Edward Nathan, Mrs, Rae De-\nButts of Lincoln, Nebraska, Mrs. William Blocker, Mrs. Pearl Maddox of\nAustin, Texas, Mrs. Hugh White, Mrs. Charles Hoke, Mrs. Fred Leggett,\nMrs. Rufus McNees, Mrs. Walter Triplett, Mrs. Forest Wingfield, Mrs.\nEduardo Villarreal, Mrs. Fred Laubert, Mrs. Harry Leach, Mrs, Duncan\nMacMillan, Mrs. J. B. MacMillan and Mrs. Robert MacMillan.\nSTATE l\ufb02w\nOFFICE NEW\nHOME SOON\nThe Texas State Employment Ser\nvice Aill move from its present\nlocation to 1106-1108 Farragut Street\nthe first of April, Mark Q. Beaubien,\u2019\nArea Manager, announced today\niThi:: expansion will facilitate the\nwork of the Employment Service,\nwhich is_affiliated with the United\nStates Employment Service. $1800\ni\u2019worth of equipment has been pur\nchased through Laredo merchants\n'and business institutions, and all to\ngether seven fulltime employees\nmake up the staff.\nLaredo as the area office super\nvises the employment work of five\ncounties, including Webb, Zapata,,\nJim Hogg, Duval, and McMullen. In\naddition to the seven employees,\nworking full time in the Laredo of\nfice, there are three employees in\nthe sub-office at Benavides.\nThere is no connection between the\nrelief organization and the Texas\nState Employment Service, Mark Q.\nBeaubien, Area Manager, said. We\nfurnish work for all types of em\nployment and Federal Highway\nConstruction Jobs. We are makingi\na special effort to develop jobs for\nwhite collar workers.\nThe Texas State Employment\nService offers to employers a system\natic and scientific method of locat\ning, classifying and referring the\nbest available workmen for any\nkind of job, Beubien pointed out.\n\u201cWe have received wonderful co\noperation from Laredo, but we can\nbe of much better service if em\nployer give us first Chance to fill\njobs as they come up. We have\nevery applicant classified, and we are\n^WHY^A^RENtT\nInvestigate My\nNO CASH DOWN PLAN\n\"-MR; BETTS Telephone!\nToday's Answers to\nCRANIUM CRACXKS\n1. Czolgosz was the assassinator of\nPresident McKinley, while Keats, By~\nron and Shelly were famous English\npoets.\n2. St. Luke was one of the 12 dis\nciple, while Rembrandt, Rubens\" and\nVan Dyke were famous painters.\n3. Gulliver was the legendary herc\nof Swift's \u201cGulliver's Travels,\u201d while\nSinclair Lewis, Rervey Allen and\nMargaret Mitchel are modern authors.\n4. Cromwell was a famous English\nstatesman, while Longfellow, Whittier\nand Lowell were American poets.\n5. David Dwubinsky is head of the\nLadies\u2019 International Garment Wor\nkers\u2019 Union, while George S. Kauf\nman, Noel Coward and Maxwell An\nderson are well-known modern play\nwrights.\nprepared to extend employment teo\na prospective applicant within an\nnotice.\u201d\nMembers of the Laredo office are\nas follows: Mark Q. Beaubien, Ares\nManager; H. R.Brown, Head Appli\ncant Relations Division; A. R. Mont\ngomery,H ead Employers Relations\ndivisioh; E. P. Berly, Interviewer,\nApplicant Relations; Eduardo Al\ndrete, Interviewer, Applicant Rela\ntions; Ruth I. Goldbeck, Clerk, Ap\nplicant Relations, Catherine Ince,\nClerk. Statistics.\nIn the sub-office, located in Be\nnavides, Miss Margaret Hudson, s\nLaredo girl, is employed to take\ncare of statistics.\nDuring February, 1938, there were\n257 new applications for jobs; 17\u20ac\u00a2\nfield visits were made to employers,\nand 125 private placements during\nFebruary, Mr. Beaubein said. An\naverage of 100 people came to the\nLaredo every day during February\nfor the purpose of registration, re\nferred to jobs. renewals of applica\ntions and filing of claims for unem\nployment compensation.","height":"20576","width":"15416"}}
